<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0840-A"><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Smith's computer chronicled the devastation.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>But Peter Vincent Pry, a staffer on the commission, argued that the nation's telecommunications systems are vulnerable and he said that other countries have taken steps to protect against e-bomb attacks &quot;indicating that this threat has broad international credibility.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>The 60 hertz goal is just &quot;a continual target, because every time somebody flips a light switch, it changes,&quot; said Paul Wattles, ERCOT's manager of governmental relations and communications.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>On a recent weekday at the Los Alamos National Laboratory, researcher Steve Fernandez took several power relay plants in the Pacific Northwest offline with a few clicks of his keyboard while Kristin Omberg and Brent Daniel were working up mathematical models that calculated the worst places to release biological agents in San Diego.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>The New York City region and all of New England should have enough electric power to supply even a record demand this summer, an organization that monitors the region's power grid said Thursday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="5" sums="12,14,30,42,44"><scu uid="8" label="New York has improved power grid monitoring" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>It turns out that the average person in Portland, population 1.6 million, has about five &quot;activities&quot; per day.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Many would speak only in general terms, saying divulging specifics could assist hackers.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>When planes crashed into the World Trade Center and Pentagon almost four years ago, the government had little understanding of the weaknesses and interdependencies of power, water, transportation and telecommunications networks.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>Security experts warned Tuesday that terrorists could unleash electromagnetic bombs to cripple the nation, damaging electrical systems vital to everything from financial services to transportation and communications.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>But in recent years, terrorists have expressed interest in a range of computer targets.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Deep inside the cave-like laboratories of the legendary research center that created the atomic bomb, scientists have begun work on a Manhattan Project of a different sort.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>They called for the creation of a major Cyber-Warfare Defense Project, modeled on the Manhattan Project, to prevent, detect and respond to potential attacks.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>Most Texans knew little of the grid until August 2003, when the nation's largest power outage caused blackouts in the Northeast.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Raacke powers his East End home with solar panels.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>A government advisory panel has concluded that a foreign intelligence service or a well-supported terrorist group &quot;could conduct a structured attack on the electric power grid electronically, with a high degree of anonymity, and without having to set foot in the target nation,&quot; according to a report last year by the Government Accountability Office, the investigative arm of Congress.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="55"><scu uid="1" label="Electrical grid control by telecommunications (internet, phone) increases vulnerability." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>Engineers monitoring the power grid in New York now have a better view of what is happening on transmission lines in neighboring states and can respond faster to offset problems that start elsewhere.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;I think it's kind of ugly,&quot; Sister Gertrude said of the bulky fuel cell out back, &quot;but I would say that the benefits greatly outweigh the aesthetics.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>And then they destroy them.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;It was a nightmare, I couldn't even see road signs,&quot; Davis said of that harrowing six-hour drive.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>But he said the agency has conducted tests and simulations, particularly on telecommunications switches, and have &quot;determined that there is minimal EMP effect.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>&quot;We just know it's being hit.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>The NRC said siren upgrades are in the works at about half the plants that lack warning systems that are fully backed up.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>Last summer was unusually cool and did not strain the system, he said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>The Los Alamos experiments are part of the Homeland Security Department's efforts to harness technology to aid the war on terror.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0187"><line>It won support from some Democrats in Congress, but it was criticized by many others and also by environmental and consumer groups, who said it gave away too much to energy companies at a time when they were benefiting from high oil prices, which neared $64 a barrel on Monday.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>They point to the 2003 blackout as an example of the devastating impact of losing power.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0187"><line>The final product did not contain a number of provisions backed by the administration, including one that would have opened a portion of the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge to oil drilling.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;Fuel cell technology provides an important link in the alternative energy chain,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Smith's program is far more detailed and uses a mixture of mathematical data and basic psychology to simulate an area and the behavior of its population.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>&quot;But I don't think enough is being done to create in-state generation.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Cyber-security specialists and government officials said that cyber-attacks are a concern across many industries but that the threat to the country's power supply is among their top fears.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>They expressed confidence, though, that demand would not exceed supply anytime soon in New York state or New England.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>As a fuel cell housed in a metal box about the size of a small SUV hummed quietly in the parking lot of the Babylon, N.Y., Town Hall with puffs of steam floating out of its exhaust pipe, the chairman of the Long Island Power Authority, Richard Kessel, announced early this month that the utility was seeking a company to build and operate a 10-megawatt fuel cell that would provide enough energy to power 10,000 homes.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="25"><scu uid="121" label="Fuel cells can be used to generate power." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>On the Net:</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>But advocates say the exercise is providing crucial information for protecting the country.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>&quot;We spend a significant amount of time and effort in making sure we are doing what we ought to do.&quot;</line><line>&quot;We feel we are in pretty good shape when it comes to this,&quot; Collins said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>That increases the risk of supply problems developing in a few areas.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>He said he agreed not to publicly disclose additional details and that the companies are fearful that releasing the information would hurt them financially and encourage more hacking.</line><line>Some utilities have made hacking into their SCADA systems relatively easy by continuing to use factory-set passwords that can be found in standard documentation available on the Internet, computer security consultants said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>It found that the department has not yet developed assessments of the threat of a cyberattack or of how vulnerable major computer systems are to such an attack, nor has it created plans for recovering key Internet functions in case of an attack.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="5" label="Homeland Security hasn't yet assessed cyberattack threats" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>The fuel cell of the future, Raacke believes, will be able to extract and store hydrogen from solar- and wind-generated energy, so if he had one in his house, he would not need to tap the grid on a cloudy day.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>If officials waited 10 days or more, Smith found, &quot;We didn't get to enough people so a lot of people died.</line><line>Day 35: 23,919 infected, 551 dead.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>&quot;At ERCOT, we're obsessed about the weather,&quot; spokeswoman Roark said, because the system needs to be ready to respond to demand.</line><line>At 60 hertz, generation matches usage exactly.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>Computers make the nation's infrastructure far more efficient, but they also make it more vulnerable.</line><line>One of the lessons of the Sept. 11 attacks in New York and Washington was how much damage a few men with simple weapons, like box cutters, could do if they targeted a point of maximum vulnerability.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>&quot;We feel comfortable from a supply-and-demand standpoint.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Ideally, the stored gas would be used on a calm or overcast day to continue powering and heating the home.</line><line>&quot;When I opened the refrigerator door, the light went on and everything inside was still cold,&quot; Dower said.</line><line>But fuel cells like those used in Long Island homes are too expensive, about $75,000, and require servicing too often to be a viable residential alternative right now, according to Roger Saillant, president and chief executive of Plug Power.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Each time the model is run, it produces more data than the contents of the Library of Congress.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>Warning messages are also spread by police car loudspeakers and radio stations.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>The biggest challenge simulation researchers face is that it's unlikely they'll ever know how accurate they were until a real attack occurs.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>&quot;Every time they test, they get in,&quot; Clarke said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;They basically created a ditch and connected pipes over a week,&quot; he said of the installation by Plug Power Inc., the Albany-based company that manufactured the fuel cells for the tests.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>Those threats come not only from terrorists but from nations with nuclear capabilities such as North Korea and Iran, the experts said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>ERCOT also continually examines the grid's reserve margins of power -- the gap between available power and forecasted usage.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>It was almost as bad as a 'do nothing' strategy, which was depressing.&quot;</line><line>You could reach in and say what I did yesterday didn't work so well and let's see how something else works,&quot; Eubank said.</line><line>In 2003, for instance, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission revealed a computer worm on the Internet penetrated the control systems of a nuclear power plant, disabling its safety mechanisms for about five hours.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"><scu uid="3" label="Cybersecurity needs to be improved." weight="4"/></annotation></line><line>Smith wondered: How would the results change if local officials closed the schools?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Before the fuel cell was hooked up, the lights in the house would flicker every day, he said, and he often had to reboot his computer.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>&quot;Fast and resolute mitigating action is needed to avoid national disaster,&quot; the scientists warned.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>Since those events, regulators and power companies have made changes in their operations designed to help them stay abreast of system conditions and head off problems.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;This will be the first project of its kind in America,&quot; Kessel said of the plan to feed fuel cell energy directly to the power grid.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="37,6"><scu uid="121" label="Fuel cells can be used to generate power." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>Wood cautioned that potential adversaries, including terrorists, have or can get nuclear weapons to generate the electromagnetic pulse.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="4" label="An electromagnetic pulse could damage electrical power systems" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>The information is so sensitive that most of the lab's work is classified, and the physical facility is secured with its own experimental technologies.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>The proposed plant, to be situated at a substation in West Babylon, is to replace a &quot;farm&quot; of 75 smaller fuel cells now being tested there.</line><line>LIPA does not expect homeowner electricity rates to increase as a result of the new project, Kessel said, even though fuel cells generate electricity at a higher cost than combustion generators.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>&quot;A sophisticated hacker, which is probably a group of hackers... could probably get into each of the three U.S. North American power (networks) and could probably bring sections of it down if they knew how to do it,&quot; said Richard Clarke, a former counterterrorism chief in the Clinton and Bush administrations.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>During mock terror attacks on plants, NRC officials assume electric power would be disrupted.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>&quot;It would be a terrorist recipe for doing something terrible,&quot; Smith said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>The fear: In a worst-case scenario, terrorists or others could engineer an attack that sets off a widespread blackout and damages power plants, prolonging an outage.</line><line>Once inside, lab workers simulated cutting off the supply of oil to a turbine generating electricity and destroying the equipment.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>&quot;It takes a certain kind of person, because they can't go out to lunch or dinner.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Under a LIPA plan that allows homeowners using solar energy to &quot;run their meters backward,&quot; Raacke feeds electricity back to the grid and gets credits on his electric bill instead of charges.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="123" label="Solar panels can be used to generate power." weight="2"/><scu uid="120" label="New York is increasing in-state generation" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>&quot;Basically, we have an inoperable emergency system at a majority of the sites,&quot; said Paul Gunter, director of the Reactor Watchdog Project for the Washington, D.C.-based Nuclear Information and Resource Service.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>An e-bomb attack could &quot;devastate this country,&quot; said Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., chairman, of the Judiciary subcommittee on terrorism, technology and homeland security, which conducted a hearing Tuesday on the potential threat.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0187"><line>On a day when oil and gasoline prices hit record highs, President Bush on Monday signed into law a bill that encourages increased domestic oil and gas production and the building of new nuclear power plants while creating incentives for alternative energy sources and requiring modernization of the nation's electrical grid.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="0,11,23,41,49,51,55"><scu uid="131" label="Alternative power sources could be a benefit" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Gordian Raacke, head of the environmental group Renewable Energy Long Island, discussed the future of fuel cells at the Babylon Town Hall news conference, where he praised LIPA's newest energy project.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>That is, they might get up and drop the children off at school, go to work, buy gas, buy groceries and then pick up the children.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>The fuel cell power has been more reliable so far.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="49"><scu uid="121" label="Fuel cells can be used to generate power." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>Protecting the nation from a potentially devastating cyberattack is not easy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>The lamp, one of several appliances in the house powered by the fuel cell sitting in the middle of the backyard, dutifully lighted the room.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>The number of potential targets is enormous.</line><line>The Government Accountability Office did a rigorous review of the Department of Homeland Security's progress on every aspect of computer security, and its findings are not reassuring.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Executives at Constellation Energy view the constant hacking attempts -- which have been unsuccessful -- as a threat and monitor their systems closely.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="3" label="Cybersecurity needs to be improved." weight="4"/></annotation></line><line>Weiss, a leading expert in control system security, said officials of the affected companies have described the instances at private conferences that he hosts and in confidential conversations but have not reported the intrusions publicly or to federal authorities.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>Experts have long warned that the nation's power, transportation and communications systems are vulnerable to &quot;cyberattacks&quot; that could devastate the economy and cause huge damage to life and property.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>Little more than a month into summer, said the report, new benchmarks for daily electricity use already have been set in Atlanta, Cincinnati, New York, Chicago and Los Angeles, among other cities.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>It begins by modeling every city block using census data, then populates the city using information on household income and age of residents.</line><line>Richard Clarke, the former counter-terrorism czar under the Clinton and Bush administrations, warned that this opened the possibility of &quot;cascade&quot; failures -- domino effects -- that authorities had little power to stop.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Saillant of Plug Power said it is indeed possible for fuel cells to store hydrogen gas taken from a mixture of water and the electrical current generated by wind turbines and solar panels.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Traditionally, estimates of infection and deaths are made using a simple multiple that denotes how fast the disease spread.</line><line>No matter how much money is spent, he said, or how long scientists work on the task, &quot;we'll never understand all the interdependencies of life.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>The utility has also already contracted with Florida Power and Light to build a windmill farm -- 40 to 50 windmill turbines -- about six miles from the Island's south shore, near Robert Moses State Park, providing 140 megawatts of power to the grid.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0187"><line>In addition to encouraging more domestic oil and gas production, it provides money for research into technology to help burn coal with less pollution and creates federal risk insurance for companies that build a new generation of nuclear power plants.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>It's a delicate balancing act to manage the scheduling of power.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>&quot;We're trying to be the best terrorists we can be,&quot; said James P. Smith, who is working on simulations of a smallpox virus released in Portland, Ore.</line><line>The Los Alamos simulations are the cornerstone of their work.</line><line>And there are virtual power grids, oil and gas lines, water pipelines, airplane and train systems -- even a virtual Internet.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>With nowhere else to go, Davis rented a car and drove with his sons to the Mineola home where the family had just moved.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>&quot;That doesn't mean we're bulletproof.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>The council projects that the maximum available supply of electricity in New York state this summer will be 39,237 megawatts, which is 7,000 megawatts more than expected peak demand and 8,000 more than have ever been used.</line><line>&quot;We think we've done just about everything we can to protect ourselves,&quot; Lynch said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Wood also has raised the issue at several public appearances.</line><line>The vulnerability of the nation's electrical grid to computer attack has grown as power companies have transferred control of their electrical generation and distribution equipment from private, internal networks to supervisory control and data acquisition, or SCADA, systems that can be accessed through the Internet or by phone lines, according to consultants and government reports.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="8" sums="10,13,19,36,43,48,54,8"><scu uid="1" label="Electrical grid control by telecommunications (internet, phone) increases vulnerability." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>If the simulations got into the wrong hands, the researchers say, they could be used as the ultimate weapon against Americans.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>The Federal Emergency Management Agency is revising warning requirements following the massive August 2003 electrical blackout in the northeastern United States.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Wood declined to comment on specifics of what he saw.</line><line>Some industry analysts play down the threat of a massive cyber-attack, saying it's more likely that terrorists would target the physical infrastructure such as power plants and transmission lines.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>Some places, too, are poorly served by transmission lines, raising concern that a rapid boost in demand could create temporary shortages.</line><line>A gigawatt represents one billion watts.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>It turned out not to have been terrorism, but the fears were well founded.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Many electric industry representatives have said they are concerned about cyber-security and have been taking steps to make sure their systems are protected.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>Studies of the outages indicated problems in Canada cascaded into the Northeast, leaving New York and Detroit without power for days.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>A well-planned cyberattack could black out large parts of the country, cut off water supplies or worse.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>The omnibus energy bill making its way through Congress also could bring changes, by putting in place enforceable electricity reliability standards that could force further improvements and spur a new generation of nuclear power plants, it added.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>The LIPA plan to use fuel cells to supply the grid is part of an effort to generate 25 percent of the utility's energy using renewable sources by 2014, a goal set by the New York state Public Service Commission last year, Kessel said.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="4" sums="13,3,35,43"><scu uid="121" label="Fuel cells can be used to generate power." weight="2"/><scu uid="120" label="New York is increasing in-state generation" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>The North American Electric Reliability Council, an industry-backed organization that sets voluntary standards for power companies, is drafting wide-ranging guidelines to replace more narrow, temporary precautions already on the books for guarding against a cyber-attack.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>More than two dozen nuclear power plants across the United States lack sirens that would warn of a nuclear emergency if electricity also was blacked out, according to a report by the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="9" sums="11,12,14,33,40,43,44,48,49"><scu uid="13" label="Some nuclear power plant sirens are dependent on electricity." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Some findings are obvious: the invention of air transportation may be the biggest factor in the spread of disease.</line><line>Next the scientists simulate people's movements on a daily basis by using data from diaries kept by commuters; foot traffic patterns on streets, malls and other public places; and public transportation schedules.</line><line>&quot;We are trying to understand the 'cost-benefit' trade-off -- if you implement a quarantine it may give you the benefit you're looking for but it may be too costly socially.&quot;</line><line>A book on public health threats by the Institute of Medicine of the National Academies, for example, notes that some critics say simulations &quot;cannot provide clear evidence for or against any option.&quot;</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>New York set a new record Tuesday of 32,075 megawatts, breaking the previous high set just last week.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>Now, he said, Congress should force all power system operators to adopt the same standards of reliability.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>While not a new threat (it was also a major concern during the Cold War), lawmakers and commissioners said that since the Sept. 11, 2001 terrorist attacks, the threat has heightened.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="20"><scu uid="130" label="Al Qaida is a threat to the power grid." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>&quot;We make sure that even if we hit a peak we have enough power to meet the demand,&quot; Roark said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>The average travel time for each person is 30 minutes.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>&quot;It's just a matter of time before we have a serious event.&quot;</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>In August 2003, a big Northeast blackout disrupted service to 50 million people.</line><line>So far, the improved planning, combined with the addition of a number of new power plants, seems to be helping the system's reliability, the report said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>Those in the control room are employees of a quasi-governmental entity called ERCOT, the Electrical Reliability Council of Texas.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Since early January, Davis' home has been one of seven in Mineola, owned by Winthrop Hospital, that are powered and heated partly by a fuel cell.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>&quot;We're in good shape for this summer,&quot; Mark S. Lynch, the president and chief executive of the system operator said in an interview Thursday.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>Despite the warnings after 9/11 -- and again after the 2003 blackout -- disturbingly little has been done.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>The scientists continuously run the simulations, which operate about 100 times faster than real time, testing actions like closing the airport, quarantining a neighborhood or shutting down workplaces.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="10" label="Terrorist attacks are being simulated using computer models" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>That's not acceptable,&quot; Eubank said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>Stable as it is, the Texas grid could be threatened by a huge storm, by multiple equipment failures or by terrorism.</line><line>But if there's an imbalance between power generation and usage, &quot;things can get pretty tense and challenging,&quot; ERCOT spokeswoman Dottie Roark said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;Having experienced a major outage, I can really appreciate this,&quot; he said.</line><line>Currently, most fuel cells extract the hydrogen from natural gas.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>But an official at the lab, Ken Watts, said the simulation showed how someone could hack into a utility's Internet-based business management system, then into a system that controls utility operations.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>&quot;The public and the Congress need to pay more attention to this danger.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>But Wood and others in the industry said the companies' computer security is uneven.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>Power grids, water treatment and distribution systems, major dams, and oil and chemical refineries are all controlled today by networked computers.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="19"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>The United States as a whole likely set a new record for weekly electricity use last week, topping by as much as 4 percent the previous record demand of 90,640 gigawatt hours, set Aug. 3, 2002, according to the Edison Electric Institute, a trade association representing major utilities.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>Plants that lack any backup power for sirens include the Indian Point plant just north of New York City and the Davis-Besse plant near Toledo, Ohio.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Hackers have caused no serious damage to systems that feed the nation's power grid, but their untiring efforts have heightened concerns that electric companies have failed to adequately fortify defenses against a potential catastrophic strike.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="10,22,30,36,43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>&quot;We're in better shape than last year,&quot; said Edward A. Schwerdt, the council's executive director.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;No lights flickering on and off anymore.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Like government &quot;data mining&quot; projects that use flight itineraries, credit card reports and other data and try to find patterns to predict who might be a likely terrorist, the simulations are attempts to guess the bigger picture.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>But as long as there's a way to get into the grid, the grid is as weak as its weakest company.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0187"><line>It extends or creates tax incentives for alternative energy sources like wind, creates incentives for the use of more ethanol and finances research into the use of hydrogen to power automobiles.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>ERCOT is responsible for making sure electric generation across the state matches the load, or usage.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>The fuel cell in his yard, hooked up through conduits and pipes in the cellar to provide heat, light and power to essential appliances in his home, did not need the LIPA grid.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>If they started mass vaccination?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Others include buildings at Brookhaven National Laboratory, a McDonald's restaurant and the Babylon Town Hall.</line><line>&quot;It closes the loop.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>&quot;Their effects on systems and infrastructures dependent on electricity and electronics could be sufficiently ruinous as to qualify as catastrophic to the nation,&quot; said Lowell Wood, acting chairman of the Commission to Assess the Threat to the United States from Electromagnetic Pulse Attack, an advisory group set up by Congress.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="20"><scu uid="4" label="An electromagnetic pulse could damage electrical power systems" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>In one simulation, Smith unleashed the smallpox virus in a university building in downtown Portland, with several students becoming victims.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="10" label="Terrorist attacks are being simulated using computer models" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Describing his reaction to the demonstration, Wood said: &quot;I wished I'd had a diaper on.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>Much of that report still has not been made public because of security concerns, commissioners said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>Experts in the control room closely monitor frequency -- the heartbeat of the system -- that reflects the relationship between electrical generation and usage.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Three days after the announcement, in the quiet living room of a house in West Islip, Sister Gertrude O'Brien flipped a switch on the reading lamp over her easy chair.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="16"/></line><line>Long Island's power demands averaged about 2,989 megawatts per hour in 2004 during peak hours.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>The intense heat wave sweeping much of the United States is pushing electricity demand to new records, a situation that is stressing the power grid, the Wall Street Journal reported Wednesday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="7" sums="23,29,30,37,42,51,6"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>The government is using the simulations to provide options in the event of a real terrorist attack.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>In some scenarios, the e-bomb could be used to release an electromagnetic pulse that could disable and damage electrical power systems.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="37,40"><scu uid="4" label="An electromagnetic pulse could damage electrical power systems" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Fernandez's work has led to upgraded security at certain power plants.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>Now a new government report has concluded that far too little is being done to close these gaps.</line><line>Rep. Zoe Lofgren, the California Democrat who was among those who requested the GAO report, said last week that it proved that &quot;a national plan to secure our cybernetworks is virtually nonexistent.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>The world is too complex, he said, to be captured that specifically in a computer program.</line><line>He advised Florida officials to position emergency repair teams in certain parts of the state he thought would receive the most damage -- and he turned out to be correct.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>(E-mail: vvaughan@express-news.net)</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>The biggest threat to the grid, analysts said, may come from power companies using older equipment that is more susceptible to attack.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="22"><scu uid="2" label="Older equipment becomes susceptible to attack" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0187"><line>The bill he signed here touches on many aspects of energy policy.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Clarke created a &quot;critical infrastructure protection&quot; group made up of the top officials from the government and from industry.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>Its control room uses sophisticated computer programs that forecast demand, plan for emergencies and make adjustments.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>The exhaust is water, heat and some carbon dioxide.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>That technology has led to greater efficiency because it allows workers to operate equipment remotely.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;When the day is overcast and I need energy, I use the credits.&quot;</line><line>But he estimates that fuel cells not requiring natural gas are, under the best federal-financing conditions, at least 15 years away.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>Texas, residents were told, is protected from power outages outside the state because the system isn't connected to other major grids in North America.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="25"><scu uid="7" label="Texas protects its grid by remaining independent" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>It also turned out the speed of intervention is much more important than the type of intervention.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>He said that if hackers destroyed generating equipment in the process, the amount of time to restore electricity could be prolonged.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Others aren't as easy to guess: shutting down schools might not help as much as expected because parents are likely to take their children to malls and playgrounds where they can come in contact with others who have been infected.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>He said computer viruses and worms also have caused problems.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>It would take a massive, coordinated, simultaneous, forced outage -- basically an act of war -- to bring down the Texas grid, a key ERCOT official has told a Texas Senate committee in response to a question about terrorism threats.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>There are virtual cities inhabited by millions of virtual individuals who go to work, shopping centers, soccer games and anywhere else their real life counterparts go.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>And because many of the targets are in private hands, the Department of Homeland Security has to work with entities that may be reluctant to follow the government's lead.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>For now in Mineola, Davis is happy with the first month of fuel cell power in his home.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0187"><line>At a ceremony at the Sandia National Laboratory here, Bush acknowledged that the measure would not immediately bring down the price of gasoline, but he said it would give the United States a start on reducing its dependence on foreign oil and help the economy over the long run.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="0"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>The whole neighborhood lost power, but Sister Gertrude and the two other nuns who live in the house could turn on their lights and watch television.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>They urged Congress and Homeland Security officials to craft plans to fend off such attacks and set up mechanisms to fix and restore power quickly.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>Twenty-eight U.S. plants lack backup power for sirens that are supposed to alert residents in a 16-kilometer (10-mile) radius of trouble, the NRC said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="13" label="Some nuclear power plant sirens are dependent on electricity." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;You can compare it to the combustion engine in a car -- billions have been built, there's an opportunity to learn from each one of them,&quot; Saillant said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>&quot;I am absolutely confident that by design, someone could do at least as (much damage), if not worse&quot; than what was experienced in 2003, said Saydjari, who was one of 54 prominent scientists and others who warned the Bush administration of the risk of computer attacks following Sept. 11, 2001.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Omberg and Daniel have created biosensors -- which can detect a wide variety of biological threats -- that have been placed in areas of major cities that the computer program calculated were vulnerable, such as near sports arenas or transportation hubs.</line><line>In September 2004, his team used the system to predict the route of Hurricane Frances based on historical information about similar hurricanes as well as its wind profile, intensity and other data 40 hours before landfall.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>When the East Coast and Midwest were hit by a blackout in 2003, the first fear of many people was that terrorists had attacked the electricity grid.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="3" sums="29,37,6"><scu uid="126" label="There was a widespread blackout in 2003" weight="2"/><scu uid="130" label="Al Qaida is a threat to the power grid." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>On a recent day at ERCOT's Austin control room, it was quiet as about half a dozen workers monitored the system.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>But computer security specialists question whether those standards go far enough.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>He found that in the event of an outbreak, targeted vaccination would work almost as well as mass vaccination if officials moved quickly to establish quarantine zones for those infected.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Baron Davis, who lives with his wife and two young sons in a home they rent in Mineola, N.Y., first came to live on Long Island from Anchorage, Alaska, in August 2003, landing at Newark (N.J.)</line><line>But while windmills create electricity from ocean winds, the fuel cells used for LIPA's project will use a fossil fuel to operate: natural gas.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>Without more local sources of power, New York will become increasingly reliant on imported electricity and could face shortages within five years, he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;Of all the fuel cells in all the world, there's probably not 2,000 of them.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>Lynch also expressed concern that not enough additional generation was planned.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>In a presentation last year to the Texas Legislature, ERCOT officials said the grid is prepared for emergencies regardless of cause.</line><line>The Texas grid covers the state except for parts of East Texas, the El Paso area and parts of the Panhandle.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="43,5"><scu uid="7" label="Texas protects its grid by remaining independent" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Those companies many not want to invest large amounts of money in new computer equipment when the machines they are using are adequately performing all their other functions.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>&quot;The thing that makes it unique is the estimate of who comes into contact with whom in a large urban area and how long the contacts last,&quot; said Stephen Eubank, a researcher at the Bioinformatics Institute at Virginia Tech who worked with Smith on the smallpox simulation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>New York should have enough power to meet the state's requirement of a cushion of 18 percent more electricity than the expected peak demand in midsummer, Durkin said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="22"><scu uid="120" label="New York is increasing in-state generation" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Soon after the 10-day incubation period passed, hospitals throughout Portland began to report cases.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>The Nuclear Regulatory Commission found that in 2003 a malicious, invasive program called the Slammer worm infected the computer network at a nuclear power plant and disabled its safety monitoring system for nearly five hours.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>In a hushed, dimly lit room in Austin, Texas, and in an identical space in nearby Taylor, people responsible for keeping the lights on in Texas intently scrutinize computer monitors 24 hours a day, seven days a week.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="14,41,44"><scu uid="1" label="Electrical grid control by telecommunications (internet, phone) increases vulnerability." weight="4"/></annotation></line><line>The workers also gaze at something more familiar: two monitors displaying The Weather Channel.</line><line>Weather patterns provide big clues to power usage.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>But he is feeling more secure these days.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>But most New Yorkers remember the August 2003 blackout that kept the city in the dark for a full day, and many worry about another one.</line><line>The council's outlook was similar in tone to a report issued last week by the New York Independent System Operator, which coordinates the flow of electricity in the state.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>The agency operates and maintains Texas' electric grid, which serves 85 percent of all of the state's electricity users and covers 75 percent of the state's sprawling geographic area.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="29"><scu uid="7" label="Texas protects its grid by remaining independent" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>The hope is to see how different social interactions are in America in 2005 from other areas where the spread of disease has been studied -- such as in rural Africa, where communities are much more isolated, or in the United States in 1918 when some cities like Portland saw much traffic from soldiers on boats.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Sister Gertrude and Father Doug, as they are called at Good Samaritan Hospital where they both work, live in hospital-owned homes that are two of several fuel cell test sites across the Island.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Hundreds of times a day, hackers try to slip past cyber-security into the computer network of Constellation Energy Group Inc., a Baltimore power company with customers around the country.</line><line>Weiss said that &quot;many utilities have not addressed control system cyber-security as comprehensively as physical security or cyber-security of business networks.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>At Three Mile Island in Middletown, the site of a March 28, 1979, partial meltdown that remains the worst U.S. nuclear plant accident, only 19 of the 96 sirens would operate if power went out.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>O. Sami Saydjari, chief executive of the Wisconsin Rapids, Wis.-based consulting firm Cyber Defense Agency LLC, said hackers could cause the type of blackout that knocked out electricity to about 50 million people in the Northeast, Midwest and Canada in 2003, an event attributed in part to trees interfering with power lines in Ohio.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>The commission released a report this past July.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, June 2:</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Some urban planners have criticized the project for its cost -- each simulation can cost tens of millions of dollars -- and have argued that such modeling can never be precise.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>&quot;We're very concerned about it,&quot; said Margaret E. &quot;Lyn&quot; McDermid, senior vice president and chief information officer for Dominion Resources Inc., a Richmond-based company that operates Dominion Virginia Power and supplies electricity and natural gas in other states.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;It really didn't create any problems.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>The grid consists of the biggest power transmission lines -- lines strung from big steel towers -- that carry as much as 345,000 volts.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line><line>ERCOT's job is to make sure the power doesn't go out in Texas.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0187"><line>The bill contains incentives for oil companies to expand refineries to reduce periodic tightness in supplies of gasoline, and tax credits for conservation and energy efficiency.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;Ever since they've had this on, I haven't seen any glitches,&quot; Davis, an unemployed electrical engineer, said of the fuel cell.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>The models have helped officials pinpoint and prioritize where changes need to be made.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>There's constant communication between ERCOT and every utility that's part of the grid.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="16,32,57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>&quot;Sometimes we finish and we're like, 'We're glad we're not terrorists.' &quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>After Sept. 11, 2001, a group of leading scientists sent a stern warning to President Bush about the danger of a computer-based terrorist attack on the nation's infrastructure.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>The groups have asked the NRC to step in and require plant owners to provide backup power to the sirens.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>&quot;I don't think anybody needs to panic,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>&quot;But if I had to do that I would basically be shooting anybody who walks out on their doorstep.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>Utility companies should not have to reduce the supply of power to businesses or residential customers unless there is an unexpected disruption or &quot;extremely hot weather conditions,&quot; said Charles Durkin, chairman of the Northeast Power Coordinating Council, a nonprofit group whose members include utility executives and regulators.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>&quot;It's true -- the Texas grid is isolated from every other state, so what happens in other regions will have no effect on us,&quot; said Mitty Plummer, associate professor of engineering technology at the University of North Texas.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>When he got inside, he checked his appliances.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Clarke said government simulations show that electric companies have not done enough to prevent hacking.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>If they locked down the whole city?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0187"><line>The measure has been one of the White House's legislative priorities since 2001.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>&quot;It's like the movie 'Groundhog Day.'</line><line>His computer was also right about the 11 days it would require to get power back up for 90 percent of the state, and about the estimate of damage: $28 billion; the final damage total was $27 billion.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>It said that the surging demand provides another big stress test for the nation's power grid.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="18,32,51"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>&quot;It's nice that the power companies think that they've done things, and some of them have.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>Energy industry officials offered no guarantees that there would not be a recurrence, because that blackout was caused by a breakdown in the transmission network that started in Ohio and cascaded to New York.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>It's ready to meet the demands of 20 million Texans; ready to deal with another peak day like that of Aug. 7, 2003, when the state's electrical usage reached a record 60,095 megawatts.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Liberty International Airport only 20 minutes after a widespread blackout had knocked out power to most of the East Coast.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Al-Qaida documents from 2002 suggest cyber-attacks on various targets, including the electrical grid and financial institutions, according to a translation by the IntelCenter, an Alexandria, Va., firm that studies terrorist groups.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="19,55"><scu uid="130" label="Al Qaida is a threat to the power grid." weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>Other systems that feed information into SCADA or that operate utility equipment are vulnerable and have been largely overlooked by utilities, security consultants said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>Experts say the United States is particularly vulnerable because it relies heavily on telecommunications and electronics.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050808.0187"><line>The Energy Department reported Monday that the average national price for a gallon of unleaded gasoline hit $2.37 last week, a record and 49 cents a gallon above prices a year ago.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Lewis said the bigger vulnerability may be posed not by outside hackers but by insiders who are familiar with their company's computer networks.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="32,40"><scu uid="3" label="Cybersecurity needs to be improved." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>Second by second, 24 hours a day, control-room experts strive to keep Texas' grid as close to 60 hertz as possible.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>Two years earlier, soaring prices and isolated blackouts rolled across California.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Officials at several power companies said they had invested heavily in new equipment and software to protect their computers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Next door, when the Rev. Douglas Dower returned to his home that same night, he noticed all the homes on his block were dark.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>The scientists build them.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>Peter Fonash, acting deputy manager for the National Communications System, Department of Homeland Security, acknowledged the potential threat.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Eubank said that when he runs simulations for governors or mayors, they inevitably ask him to quarantine the whole city, to make sure residents stay in their houses.</line><line>Day 1: 1,281 infected, zero dead.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>Above them hangs a bank of displays 16 feet high by 32 feet wide that silently blink with changing data impenetrable to the average person.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050308.0154"><line>Some of its recommendations include the government buying backup transformers to be stored in protected shelters and crafting a plan to use diesel electric motors.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>Still, the report said that the run-up in demand is using up a cushion of surplus power that has moderated prices in recent years.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>&quot;We could lose any single, major element of the system -- one outage caused by a tornado or sabotage -- and it wouldn't put us at risk,&quot; said Kent Saathoff, ERCOT's director of systems operations.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>They said they assume many of the hackers are the same type seen in other businesses: people who view penetrating corporate systems as fun or a challenge.</line><line>Officials will not say whether new intelligence points to a potential terrorist strike, but Wood stepped up his campaign after officials at the Energy Department's Idaho National Laboratory showed him how a skilled hacker could cause serious problems.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Smith programmed a cluster of computers to run through these scenarios and hundreds of others, trying to determine which response would save the most lives.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Fuel cells are &quot;clean&quot; energy generators that convert hydrogen to electricity by a chemical process, requiring no combustion.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050727.0268"><line>The surge reflects not just the unusually widespread heat, but also a recent upward creep in industrial electricity usage, the report said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>The public service commission includes fuel cells in its policy, a commission spokesman, David Flanagan, said, to spur the development of cells that will one day run on renewable resources like methane or electrical current.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>In a well-planned cyberattack, a single terrorist with nothing more than a computer and Internet access could do an extraordinary amount of harm from half a world away.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Hackers have gained access to U.S. utilities' electronic control systems and in a few cases have &quot;caused an impact,&quot; said Joseph Weiss, a Cupertino, Calif.-based computer security specialist with Kema Inc., a consulting firm focused on the energy industry.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>For the entire Northeast, the council projected that demand would peak in the week of July 10 at 106,618 megawatts, leaving a cushion of more than 9,000 megawatts of capacity.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>&quot;ERCOT is digesting real-time data from everybody, and they'll change generation patterns to match the load,&quot; said Bill Woolsey, assistant chief transmission operator at CPS, the electric utility in San Antonio.If there's a drastic, non-routine mismatch -- too much usage and not enough power generation, or vice versa -- &quot;it can cascade into a lot of problems,&quot; Woolsey said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Fernandez said the pinpoint accuracy of the Hurricane Frances simulation was just plain luck.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>They pretty much live here for 12 hours.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Day 70: 380,582 infected, 12,499 dead.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>&quot;We're taking fuel cells to a new level.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>James Andrew Lewis, director of technology policy at the Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington D.C., said a coordinated attack on the grid would be technically difficult and would not provide as much &quot;bang for the buck&quot; as high-profile physical attacks.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>The technological challenges are considerable -- even major technology companies have trouble defending themselves against hackers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>At ERCOT's control centers in Taylor -- a bunkerlike building designed to withstand a Force 3 tornado with winds up to 206 mph -- and its backup center in Austin, computer programs help workers monitor electrical generation and usage.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050428.0314"><line>In addition, Lynch said, several improvements have been made to try to prevent another disaster like the blackout of 2003.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="23"><scu uid="126" label="There was a widespread blackout in 2003" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>Todd Schneider, spokesman for Davis-Besse, said the sirens are only one part of an emergency plan.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050712.0138"><line>As the first hot days of Texas summer count down to the scorching temperatures of late July and August, ERCOT managers say the grid is prepared.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>That same year, much of the East Coast and Midwest were hit with an electrical blackout that experts thought should have been limited to one area.</line><line>In the wake of Sept. 11, 2001, they have been constructing the most elaborate computer models of the United States ever attempted.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>Seventeen plants have full backup for the systems, while 18 others have at least some sirens that would remain operable during an outage.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>The main function of the tests is to improve the technology.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>But overcoming these obstacles should be a high priority.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>Smith's findings have been a major component of the debate over whether it's necessary to synthesize enough smallpox vaccine for the entire country.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>Working sirens would be crucial since a loss of electricity can challenge nuclear plants' safety shutdown systems and heighten the risk of a core-melting accident, nuclear watchdog groups said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050703.0028"><line>The only system that's been tested against a real life event is Fernandez's program for how hurricanes will affect the electricity grid.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="35,43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>Patrick H. Wood III, the chairman of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, warned top electric company officials in a private meeting in January that they need to focus more heavily on cyber-security.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050527.0591"><line>The NRC released the information Wednesday as part of its response to a coalition of 17 activist groups and elected officials that petitioned the commission in February for information about the siren systems.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050311.0029"><line>&quot;We have no discernable way of knowing who is trying to hit our system,&quot; said John Collins, chief risk officer for Constellation, which operates Baltimore Gas and Electric.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050212.0164"><line>Those benefits were visible on a day in December when a car hit a utility pole nearby.</line><line>&quot;I don't pay anything for electricity,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050602.0007"><line>The report also expressed concern that many of the department's senior cybersecurity officials have left in the past year.</line></document></collection>